<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: NEW DELHI; A PRINCELY PUSH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 India, wags once said, seemed to have been expressly created to provide the 
British ruling classes with a venue for outdoor sports, none of which was more 
prized than shikar -- hunting. 
</P>
<P>
 The world, though, has changed. Britain's Prince Philip, president of the 
World Wildlife Fund, will address India's "first national conservation 
congress" Wednesday. The prince is taking part in events marking the 25th 
anniversary of the World Wide Fund for Nature-India. 
</P>
<P>
 The three-day meeting will cover dangers to biodiversity, the effects of 
industry and a fast-growing population on nature and efforts to educate people 
about wildlife and other issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
