<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: SANTA FE SPRINGS; PLAN 
TO CLEAN UP CHEMICAL COMPANY SITE UNVEILED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 State and federal environmental officials have unveiled a plan for cleaning up 
contaminated soil and ground water at a Santa Fe Springs chemical company. 
</P>
<P>
 The California Environmental Protection Agency and the U.S. Environmental 
Protection Agency are proposing that Phibro-Tech Inc. pump and treat ground 
water to remove contaminants, including cadmium, chromium and trichloroethane. 
</P>
<P>
 The agencies propose that Phibro-Tech investigate and, if necessary, clean up 
volatile contaminants in the soil. The plan also calls for monitoring soil and 
ground water, covering any unpaved portions of the site to prevent contact with 
contaminated soil, repairing the site cover, constructing a berm around the 
perimeter of the facility and restricting property use to prevent any school or 
residential developments. 
</P>
<P>
 The public may comment on the proposed cleanup plan by submitting written 
comments by Dec. 30 to Cal-EPA, or by attending a Dec. 13 community meeting. 
The meeting will begin at 7 p.m. at the Los Nietos Community and Senior 
Citizens Services in Whittier. 
</P>
<P>
 Phibro-Tech, a division of CP Chemicals Inc. of New Jersey, is in an 
industrial area at 8851 Dice Road in Santa Fe Springs. 
</P>
<P>
 The company produces a variety of inorganic chemicals used in the aerospace 
and electronics industries and also stores and treats off-site generated 
hazardous waste from those facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
