<HEADLINE>
<P>
SUPPORTING THE BASES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Let me see if I got this right. Ventura County is spending 300,000 of its 
taxpayers' hard-earned dollars to send some lobbyists to Washington, D.C. Their 
mission is to lobby the commission charged with the closure of military bases 
to leave Point Mugu and Port Hueneme off the list.  
</P>
<P>
 Excuse me, but isn't that the reason we have elected representatives? I mean, 
Elton Gallegly (R-Simi Valley) surely must be aware that these military bases 
are on the list. And one would assume that the reason he was elected in the 
first place is to act as ombudsman for Ventura County and to represent Ventura 
County's best interests. Why do we need lobbyists if we have Elton? Or why do 
we need Elton if we have lobbyists? 
</P>
<P>
 Surely Elton Gallegly and his staff are not so overburdened with legislative 
activities that they are unable to represent the best interests of the 
constituency. I seem to remember when Bob Lagomarsino represented this district 
prior to the gerrymander, that he argued successfully against the base 
closures. 
</P>
<P>
 My message to the county supervisors is this: Quit (wasting) the taxpayers' 
money on items that we already pay for through the nose. And the message to 
Elton is: Quit playing partisan politics and get on with the job of 
representing the citizens of Ventura County. 
</P>
<P>
 The military bases in Ventura County are not insignificant to the economic 
structure of this county and if they are closed during Elton Gallegly's watch, 
the voters will not soon forget. 
</P>
<P>
 GARY WOLLARD 
</P>
<P>
 Camarillo 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 I would like to see all residents of Port Hueneme who work at either of the 
two bases send $5 for each person in the household working on the base to the 
BRAC 95 Task Force at 5000 Santa Rosa Road, Suite B-471, Camarillo, CA 93012. 
</P>
<P>
 I believe the residents need to show their support for the task force. There 
are, according to the county, 5,000 people with a Port Hueneme address who work 
on one of the two Navy bases: 5,000 x $5 = $25,000. 
</P>
<P>
 That would go a long way to help the task force raise enough money to hire the 
Washington consultants that will help keep these bases off the list and from 
being added to the list. 
</P>
<P>
 As my husband works at CBC, I have put my money in the mail. I hope all the 
residents who work on one of the bases will do the same. 
</P>
<P>
 Let's make it clear: Port Hueneme supports the BRAC 95 Task Force's efforts. 
</P>
<P>
 TONI YOUNG 
</P>
<P>
 Port Hueneme 
</P>
<P>
 Toni Young is a member of the Port Hueneme City Council.  
</P>
