<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOUR MONEY; SPOTLIGHT ON TAXES; FACTS ABOUT CASUALTY LOSSES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kathy Kristof 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THE RULES: You get a tax deduction for unreimbursed losses from sudden, 
unusual and unexpected events, such as fires, floods, earthquakes and 
tornadoes.  
</P>
<P>
 THE LIMITATIONS: The deductible portion of the loss is the amount that exceeds 
10% of your adjusted gross income plus $100 per casualty.In other words, if you 
earn $50,000, you must subtract $5,100 from your unreimbursed loss. You can 
deduct the result.  
</P>
<P>
 THE TRICKS: To determine your total loss you must either get appraisals of the 
property's value, or you must establish the cost of repairing the damage. If 
the decline in value or the cost of repair exceeds the amount you paid for the 
property, you can deduct the lesser of the two. 
</P>
<P>
 THE CAVEATS: Casualty losses are widely believed to be audit triggers, 
singling out your return for special scrutiny by the IRS. This shouldn't 
discourage you from claiming a legitimate loss. But you should be sure to 
maintain particularly clear and detailed tax records in any year that you claim 
a casualty loss. Kathy Kristof 
</P>
</TEXT>
